    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (80.98) standing as our most efficient offensive engine. His matchup against the right-handed Me Kelly is ideal, bolstered by a 10% boost from wind-out conditions and a high stolen base probability against a pitcher with a slow delivery. Following closely is **Junior Caminero** (73.06), whose pedigree against right-handed pitching provides significant value despite a slight park penalty, and **Trea Turner** (69.27), whose prime leadoff spot against the hittable Paddack keeps him locked into a high-scoring tier. We are also monitoring **Colt Keith** (65.82) and **Kyle Schwarber** (65.78) closely; both benefit significantly from favorable matchups against righties, and in the case of **Colt Keith**, the slow delivery of the opposing pitcher makes him a prime target for stolen base contribution.\n\nOur most difficult bench decision involved **Jerar Encarnacion** (42.40), who narrowly missed the cut. While his platoon advantage against the left-handed Matz was noted, his efficiency score fell short of our middle infield and outfield starters, who offer higher upside in stolen base opportunities\u2014our scarcest category. **Dillon Dingler** (46.93) and **Kazuma Okamoto** (46.93) round out the lower end of our starting group; while their base projections are solid, their scores are dampened by dynamic platoon splits and tough opposing starters like Leiter and Ryan, respectively. We continue to hold **Christian Yelich** and **Zac Veen** on the bench due to IL and minor league assignments, leaving our active roster to carry the heavy lifting against today\u2019s opposing pitchers.\n\nWe remain cautious regarding the \"Lineup Pending\" status for **Dillon Dingler**, **Colt Keith**, **Chase Meidroth**, and **Carson Benge**. While we have modeled their scores based on historical batting orders, any late-breaking changes\u2014particularly for **Chase Meidroth** (49.07) or **Carson Benge** (62.65)\u2014could necessitate a real-time adjustment. We are also keeping a close eye on **Yordan Alvarez** (60.46); despite facing a left-handed pitcher which creates a platoon disadvantage, his elite xwOBA remains a stabilizing force that prevents us from considering a benching. As always, our priority remains the preservation of game caps, so we will be ready to rotate in **Luke Raley**, **Lars Nootbaar**, **Luis Pena**, or **Pedro Ramirez** should any of our primary starters be scratched before first pitch.",
